To use Git effectively in DevOps, you need the following core elements:
1. The Right Tooling
Git CLI: You must have Git installed on your local machine (Windows, macOS, or Linux) to run commands.
Remote Hosting Service: A platform to host your code centrally, such as Azure Repos, GitHub, or GitLab.
Authentication: Secure access using SSH keys or Personal Access Tokens (PATs) to avoid entering passwords manually for every push or pull. 

2. A Solid Branching Strategy
DevOps relies on isolation and stability. You should never work directly on the main branch. 
Feature Branches: Created for specific tasks (e.g., feature/login-api) to keep experiments isolated.
Trunk-Based Development: A popular DevOps model where short-lived branches are merged quickly into the "trunk" (main branch) to maintain a fast flow.
Pull Requests (PRs): These are mandatory in DevOps for team review and to trigger automated validation tests before code is merged. 

3. Integrated CI/CD Triggers
Your repository must be configured to talk to your automation tools.
Webhooks: These notify your CI/CD tool (like Jenkins or GitHub Actions) immediately when an event like a push or merge occurs.
Pipeline Definitions: Storing your CI/CD configuration (like azure-pipelines.yml or .github/workflows/ci.yml) directly in the repository so they are version-controlled. 

4. Versioned Everything (GitOps)
In DevOps, you don't just store application code; you use Git to manage: 
Infrastructure as Code (IaC): Terraform modules, CloudFormation templates, or Ansible playbooks.
Kubernetes Manifests: YAML files that define how your containers should run.
Configuration Files: Environment-specific settings that can be tracked and audited. 

5. Best Practices & Hygiene
Clear Commit Messages: Messages should explain why a change was made, which is vital for auditing and rollbacks.
No Secrets in Git: Never commit API keys or passwords; use Azure Key Vault or GitHub Secrets instead.
Small, Frequent Commits: This makes it easier to identify which change broke a build and allows for faster recovery.


In DevOps, Git is the "single source of truth" for application code, infrastructure as code (IaC), and
CI/CD pipeline definitions. Below is a comprehensive list of Git commands categorized by their role in a typical DevOps
workflow.

1. Configuration & Setup
Before starting, you must identify yourself so that your contributions are properly tracked. 

* git config --global user.name "Your Name": Sets your name for all commits.
* git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com": Sets your email.
* git init: Initializes a new local Git repository in the current directory.
* git clone <url>: Creates a local copy of a remote repository (e.g., from Azure Repos or [GitHub](https://github.com/)). [3, 4, 5, 6, 7] 

2. The Core Developer Workflow
Use these commands for daily tasks like staging and saving changes.

* git status: Shows the state of the working directory and staging area (tracked/untracked files).
* git add <file>: Stages specific changes; use git add . to stage all changes.
* git commit -m "message": Records your staged changes in the local repository history.
* git commit --amend: Modifies the most recent commit (useful for fixing typos or adding forgotten files). 

3. Branching & Collaboration
Branching allows you to work on features or fixes without affecting the main codebase. 

* git branch: Lists all local branches.
* git checkout -b <branch-name>: Creates a new branch and switches to it immediately.
* git switch <branch-name>: A modern, clearer alternative to checkout for switching branches.
* git merge <branch>: Combines changes from the specified branch into your current branch.
* git rebase <branch>: Reapplies your commits on top of another branch to maintain a linear history. 

4. Remote Syncing & CI/CD Triggers
These commands are essential for interacting with remote servers and triggering [automated pipelines](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/pipelines/scripts/git-commands?view=azure-devops). [16, 17] 

* git remote add origin <url>: Links your local repository to a remote server.
* git fetch: Downloads updates from the remote repository without merging them.
* git pull: Fetches and immediately merges changes from the remote repository.
* git push origin <branch>: Uploads local commits to the remote repository, often triggering a CI/CD build.
* git push --tags: Pushes version tags, often used to trigger specific production deployment pipelines. 

5. Inspection, Undo & Maintenance
Essential for debugging and keeping the repository clean.

* git log --oneline --graph: Displays a visual, concise history of commits.
* git diff: Shows differences between the working directory and the staging area.
* git stash: Temporarily shelves uncommitted changes so you can switch contexts quickly.
* git revert <commit-id>: Undoes changes by creating a new commit (safest for public branches).
* git reset --hard HEAD~1: Discards the last commit and all associated changes (use with caution).
* git clean -fd: Removes untracked files and directories to clean the local environment.
* git gc: Runs "garbage collection" to optimize the repository and reduce its size.
